audit.name: SSLv2 Detected
audit.description: Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2 has been detected. This protocol is known to have cryptographic weaknesses as well as other exploitable vulnerabilities.
audit.fixInformation:
Ensure that applications or services are configured to reject SSL version 2 communications.

Note: Most implementations of SSL will provide support for all versions of the protocol. It is up to the application to decide what versions of the protocol it will support and/or refuse. When an SSL connection is negotiated, the client first asks the server application if it will support a certain version of the protocol. This is known as the "handshake". If the server responds that the version is supported, then credentials/keys are exchanged to complete the connection.

Some server applications, such as IIS, will reject the initial handshake based on its protocol configuration. Other server applications attempt to exchange keys before determining if it will support the requested version of the SSL protocol.

Since SSLv2 exploits are normally based on the initial handshake, Retina relies on the response from the handshake request to ascertain a potential vulnerability. Because of this, an application that is configured to reject SSLv2 could still report as vulnerable.

audit.name: Host Accepts TCP SYN FIN Requests
audit.description: The host appears to accept TCP SYN FIN requests from remote hosts. This TCP Option combination is often considered malicious and used by remote scanners to detect open TCP ports and services. These requests should be considered malicious and blocked by a stateful packet inspector or firewall or IPS system.
audit.fixInformation: Configure the host's firewall, IPS, or stateful packet inspector (hardware or otherwise) to block TCP SYN FIN requests.

audit.name: POP3 Service Detected
audit.description: Retina has detected a Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) service listening on the target system. POP3 is inherently insecure as it transmits all usernames, passwords, and data unencrypted (i.e. plain-text).
audit.fixInformation: If POP3 is not necessary on the target, disable it. Consult your user's manual or system help files for information on how to disable your POP3 service. If no user's manual or help file exists, contact your system vendor.

audit.name: PHP Multiple Vulnerabilities (20130221) - Banner
audit.description: PHP contains multiple vulnerabilities when validating the relationship between the soap.wsdl_cache_dir directive and the oopen_basedir directive, and when handling crafted SOAP WSDL files containing an XML external entity declaration. Successful exploitation may allow an attacker to read arbitrary files or privilege escalation.
audit.fixInformation: Update PHP to version 5.4.13, 5.3.23, or newer.

audit.name: PHP Buffer Overflow Vulnerability (20130606) - Remote
audit.description: PHP before 5.4.16 and 5.3.26 contains a heap-based buffer overflow in the "php_quot_print_encode()" function when parsing passed strings. Successful exploitation may result in execution of arbitrary code or a denial of service condition.
audit.fixInformation: Upgrade to PHP 5.4.16, 5.3.26 or newer.

audit.name: PHP XML Parsing Vulnerability (20130712) - Banner
audit.description: PHP contains a vulnerability in xml.c when handling a crafted document that's processed by the 'xml_parse_into-struct' function. Successful exploitation may allow a remote attacker to create denial-of-service conditions or execute arbitrary code via a heap-based buffer overflow.
audit.fixInformation: Update 5.3.x versions of PHP to 5.3.27 or newer and 5.4.x versions of PHP to 5.4.16 or newer.

audit.name: PHP Multiple Vulnerabilities (20130819)
audit.description: PHP before 5.5.2 contains a session fixation vulnerability and a spoofing vulnerability in the openssl_x509_parse function. Successful exploitation may result in arbitrary SSL servers spoofing or session hijacking.
audit.fixInformation: Upgrade to PHP 5.5.2 or later.

audit.name: nginx URI Verification Bypass Vulnerability (20131120) - Remote
audit.description: nginx does not properly verify request URIs containing unescaped space characters. Successful exploitation may result in information leakage.
audit.fixInformation: Upgrade to nginx 1.4.4, 1.5.7, or later.

audit.name: PHP Multiple Vulnerabilities (20140214) - Remote
audit.description: PHP does not properly check return values, does not properly check data types, contains an integer overflow and signedness errors in the 'gdImageCrop' function, and does not properly restrict access to the libxml RSHUTDOWN function. Successful exploitation may result in a denial of service condition or information leakage.
audit.fixInformation: Upgrade to PHP 5.4.25, 5.5.9, or later.

audit.name: SSL/TLS RC4 Cipher Suites Supported
audit.description: The remote host allows the use of RC4 cipher suites. The RC4 cipher generation of a pseudo-random stream of bytes is flawed to allow small biases into the stream, decreasing its randomness. If plaintext is encrypted over and over and an attacker is able to obtain millions of ciphertexts, the attacker may be able to retrieve the plaintext from the stream.
audit.fixInformation: If possible, disable the use of RC4 ciphers in the application or its host operating system.

audit.name: SSL/TLS EXPORT_RSA <= 512-bit Cipher Suites Supported
audit.description: This vulnerability, also known as the FREAK vulnerability, indicates that the remote host supports EXPORT_RSA cipher suites with keys <= 512 bits. An attacker can factor a 512-bit RSA modulus quickly, thus allowing him to perform a man-in-the middle attack that may be able to downgrade the SSL session to use EXPORT_RSA cipher suites.
audit.fixInformation: Reconfigure the service to remove support for EXPORT_RSA cipher suites.

audit.fixInformation: This is an informational check. No action is required.

audit.name: SSL Certificate Expires Within One-to-Three Months
audit.description: Retina has detected that the targeted SSL service is using a certificate that expires within three months.
audit.fixInformation: Remove and/or replace the existing certificate with a renewed certificate from a trusted certificate authority. Ensure that the renewed certificate is used on its proper date of validity (i.e. ValidFrom date).

audit.name: OpenSSL DROWN Vulnerability Detected
audit.description: Retina has detected that the targeted service accepts connections for SSLv2 which can allow remote attackers to perform a “Decrypting RSA with Obsolete and Weakened eNcryption” (DROWN) attack.
audit.fixInformation: Disable SSLv2 support on the affected target.

audit.name: FreeBSD: nginx < 1.10.1 DoS
audit.description: A problem was identified in nginx code responsible for saving client request body to a temporary file. A specially crafted request might result in worker process crash while writing client request body to a temporary file.
audit.fixInformation: Update to version 1.11.1 or 1.10.1
